The main objective of this assignment is to:¶

Build an appropriate deep neural network for analyzing movie reviews using the provided dataset. Consider preprocessing the data, choosing between regression or classification architectures, and deciding whether to include only English reviews or consider other languages as well.

I am building a classification RNN model for classifying sentiment of Movie Reviews because sentiment analysis typically involves discrete categories (positive, negative, neutral), making classification more suitable than regression.¶

Research and Background¶

  • RNNs in NLP: Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs) are commonly used for sequential data analysis tasks, including natural language processing (NLP) tasks like sentiment analysis.
  • Text Preprocessing: Preprocessing steps like tokenization, stopword removal, and word embeddings are crucial for extracting meaningful features from text data.
  • Multilingual Analysis: Consider the language diversity in the dataset and decide whether to focus solely on English reviews or include other languages for analysis.

EDA and Preprocessing¶

  • Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA): Explore the movie review dataset to understand sentiment label distributions, word frequencies, and potential preprocessing requirements.
  • Text Preprocessing: Tokenize text, handle stopwords, and apply word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec, GloVe) to represent words numerically for model input.

Model Architecture and Training¶

  • RNN Architecture: Choose appropriate RNN architectures such as Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) or Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU) for sentiment analysis tasks.
  • Hyperparameter Tuning: Optimize hyperparameters like sequence length, embedding dimensions, and RNN units to enhance model performance.
  • Language Consideration: Decide whether to include multilingual analysis and justify this decision based on the dataset's language diversity.

Evaluation and Improvement¶

  • Model Evaluation: Evaluate the trained RNN models using validation metrics like accuracy, F1 score, or mean squared error (MSE) for regression tasks.
  • Model Improvement: Experiment with different word embeddings, regularization techniques (e.g., dropout), and optimization strategies to improve model accuracy and generalization.

Observation:

From the Score Distribution graphs, it becomes evident that the distribution of Scores is highly skewed towards the lower end, particularly within the range of 0 to 0.1.

Hence, I would be trying to create more data for between 0.1 to 1

From the Language Distribution graph shows that there is a significant amount of data for Malay and English, whereas Chinese and Nippon (Japanese) are notably sparse, with very few data points, almost zero.

Hence, as there is not enough data to train RNN models with very little data, I would be dropping rows with Language of Chinese and Nippon (Japanese).

As if any models are created based on very little data, the models are very likely to be inaccurate and biased.

# Function to preprocess text and generate new data
def preprocess_text(text):
    # Convert to lowercase
    text = text.lower()
    # Remove mentions
    text = re.sub("@\S+", " ", text)
    # Remove URL
    text = re.sub("https*\S+", " ", text)
    # Remove hashtags
    text = re.sub("#\S+", " ", text)
    # Remove all numbers
    text = re.sub("\d", " ", text)
    # Remove punctuations
    text = re.sub('[%s]' % re.escape(string.punctuation), ' ', text)
    # Remove extra spaces
    text = re.sub('\n', ' ', text)
    text = re.sub('\s{2,}', ' ', text)
    return text

# Define sentiment categories based on score
def get_sentiment(score):
    if score < 0.2:
        return 'positive'
    elif 0.2 <= score <= 0.6:
        return 'neutral'
    else:
        return 'negative'

# Initialize the synonym augmenter
aug = naw.SynonymAug(aug_src='wordnet')

# Function to augment data for a class
def augment_data(df_class, target_count):
    augmented_texts = []
    while len(df_class) + len(augmented_texts) < target_count:
        for _, row in df_class.iterrows():
            if len(df_class) + len(augmented_texts) >= target_count:
                break
            augmented_text = aug.augment(row['Review'])
            augmented_texts.append([augmented_text[0], row['Score'], row['Language'], row['Sentiment']])
    return pd.DataFrame(augmented_texts, columns=['Review', 'Score', 'Language', 'Sentiment'])

# Function to balance datasets by sentiment
def balance_datasets_by_sentiment(df, target_count):
    sentiments = ['positive', 'neutral', 'negative']
    balanced_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Review', 'Score', 'Language', 'Sentiment'])

    for sentiment in sentiments:
        df_sentiment = df[df['Sentiment'] == sentiment]
        if len(df_sentiment) < target_count:
            df_augmented = augment_data(df_sentiment, target_count)
            df_combined = pd.concat([df_sentiment, df_augmented])
        else:
            df_combined = df_sentiment.sample(target_count, random_state=88)
        balanced_df = pd.concat([balanced_df, df_combined])

    return balanced_df

# Set the target count for each sentiment
max_count = 200

# Balance the datasets for English reviews
english_balanced = balance_datasets_by_sentiment(english_reviews, max_count)

# Balance the datasets for Malay reviews
malay_balanced = balance_datasets_by_sentiment(malay_reviews, max_count)

Creating Embedding Matrix¶

Create an embedding matrix* based on the GloVe and FastText embeddings.*

GloVe file downloaded from: https://nlp.stanford.edu/projects/glove/ and https://fasttext.cc/docs/en/crawl-vectors.html

.Initialize it with zeros* and fill in the embeddings for words that exist in the vocabulary.*

In [18]:
# Importing GloVe embedding file
path_to_glove_file = './glove.6B.100d.txt'

embeddings_index = {}
with open(path_to_glove_file, encoding='utf-8') as f:
    for line in f:
        values = line.split()
        word = values[0]
        coefs = np.asarray(values[1:], dtype='float32')
        embeddings_index[word] = coefs

print('Found %s word vectors.' % len(embeddings_index))

english_embedding_dim = 100

# Create embedding matrix for English dataset
english_embedding_matrix = np.zeros((len(english_word_index) + 1, english_embedding_dim))
print(english_word_index)


for word, i in english_word_index.items():
    embedding_vector = embeddings_index.get(word)
    if embedding_vector is not None:
        english_embedding_matrix[i] = embedding_vector

print("English embedding matrix shape:", english_embedding_matrix.shape)

Confusion Matrix Plot Function¶

In [24]:
# Function to plot confusion matrix
def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, class_names):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap='Blues', xticklabels=class_labels, yticklabels=class_labels)
    plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
    plt.ylabel('True Label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')
    plt.show()

Building and Training the Model¶

Building and training the LSTM model using Keras

My model consists of:

  • 1 Embedding input layer
  • 1 LSTM layer
  • 1 Dense layer
In [40]:
# Set the seed for reproducibility
seed = 88
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed)

num_classes=3

# Creating baseline model
model = Sequential()
model.add(Embedding(len(english_word_index) + 1, english_embedding_dim, input_length=MAX_SEQUENCE_LENGTH, weights=[english_embedding_matrix], trainable=False))
model.add(LSTM(100, dropout=0.2, recurrent_dropout=0.2))
model.add(Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))

model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()

history=model.fit(x_train, y_train, epochs=20, batch_size=64, validation_data=(x_test,y_test))

# Plot accuracy
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.suptitle('English Reviews')
plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'], label='Train')
plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'], label='Test')
plt.title('Model Accuracy')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.show()

# Predict the output on the test set
predictions = model.predict(x_test)
predicted_classes = np.argmax(predictions, axis=1)

# Get the true labels
true_classes = y_test

class_labels=labels_dict.keys()

# Compute the confusion matrix
cm = confusion_matrix(true_classes, predicted_classes)

# Plot confusion matrix
plot_confusion_matrix(cm, class_labels)

# Evaluate the model on the test set
test_loss, test_accuracy = model.evaluate(x_test, y_test)

# Print the test accuracy and error rate
print(f'Test Accuracy: {test_accuracy:.4f}')
print(f'Error Rate: {(1 - test_accuracy):.4f}')

Model Improvement¶

My improved model consists of:

  • 1 Embedding input layer
  • 2 LSTM layer
  • 2 Dense layer
  • 1 Dropout layer

I added an extra LSTM layer to capture deeper patterns and a dropout layer to prevent overfitting, enhancing model complexity and generalization

In [29]:
# Set the seed for reproducibility
seed = 88
np.random.seed(seed)
tf.random.set_seed(seed)

# Creating a more complex model for English reviews
model = Sequential()
model.add(Embedding(len(english_word_index) + 1, english_embedding_dim, input_length=MAX_SEQUENCE_LENGTH, weights=[english_embedding_matrix], trainable=False))
model.add(LSTM(300, return_sequences=True, dropout=0.2, recurrent_dropout=0.2))  
model.add(LSTM(100, dropout=0.2, recurrent_dropout=0.2))  
model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))  
model.add(Dropout(0.2))  
model.add(Dense(3, activation='softmax'))  

model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()

# Define early stopping callback
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_accuracy', patience=20, verbose=2, restore_best_weights=True)

# Fit the model with early stopping
history = model.fit(x_train, y_train, epochs=100, batch_size=64, validation_data=(x_test,y_test), callbacks=[early_stopping])

# Plot accuracy

# Define the function to create the Keras model with hyperparameters
def build_model(hp):
    model = Sequential([
        Embedding(len(english_word_index) + 1, english_embedding_dim, input_length=MAX_SEQUENCE_LENGTH, weights=[english_embedding_matrix], trainable=False),
        LSTM(300, return_sequences=True, dropout=hp.Float('dropout_1', 0.1, 0.3, step=0.1), recurrent_dropout=hp.Float('recurrent_dropout_1', 0.1, 0.3, step=0.1)),
        LSTM(100, dropout=hp.Float('dropout_2', 0.1, 0.3, step=0.1), recurrent_dropout=hp.Float('recurrent_dropout_2', 0.1, 0.3, step=0.1)),
        Dense(hp.Int('dense_units', 32, 128, step=32), activation='relu'),
        Dropout(hp.Float('dropout_dense', 0.1, 0.3, step=0.1)),
        Dense(3, activation='softmax')
    ])
    
    model.compile(optimizer=hp.Choice('optimizer', ['adam', 'rmsprop']),
                  loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

# Initialize the Keras Tuner
tuner = RandomSearch(
    build_model,
    objective='val_accuracy',
    max_trials=8,
    executions_per_trial=1,
    directory='keras_tuner_english_results',  
    project_name='english_rnn_tuning'
)

# Define early stopping callback
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_accuracy', patience=20, restore_best_weights=True, verbose=2)

# Perform hyperparameter tuning
tuner.search(x_train, y_train, epochs=100, validation_data=(x_test, y_test), callbacks=[early_stopping], verbose=2)

# Retrieve the best model
best_model = tuner.get_best_models(num_models=1)[0]

# Function to preprocess the review
def preprocess_review(review, word_index, max_sequence_length):
    tokens = review.split()  # Tokenize the review
    sequences = [word_index.get(token, 0) for token in tokens]  # Convert tokens to integers
    padded_sequence = pad_sequences([sequences], maxlen=max_sequence_length, padding='post')
    return padded_sequence

new_review = "This movie was fantastic and thrilling!"

# Predict the sentiment
